"Just under a half of businesses have not developed corporate recovery plans to deal with catastrophic events according to a report issued by the UK Chartered Management Institute (CMI) in March 2005. The survey of 440 managers, conducted by the Continuity Forum and Veritas Software, ranged from sole traders to companies employing more than 10,000 employees. The Survey found that just over three-quarters of financial institutions have business continuity plans – twice as many as retail companies. The lessons of the terrorist attacks on the New York World Trade Center and the IRA bombs that devastated parts of the City of London in the 1990s are apparently still not learned."
